**Who Follows Who?**  
**![][image1]**

This is a website using NPM’s JSZip package to display people who have unfollowed you or people you have unfollowed. This website takes in a zip file from Instagrams downloading information feature containing json files to then extract that information about followers.json and following.json and display the correct data regarding the user.

***How It Works Explanation:***   
	  
	Initially the JS imports JSZip for use, and creates the initApp() to initialize everything once the content is loaded through an eventListener for DOMContentLoaded and the call to initApp(). 

Defines the dropArea through getElementById, and initializes the active and inactive phases by making it a value which adds the class of red-border so when objects are dragged over the drop-area colors change. Additionally there is a preventDefault constant created. For any of the possible, ‘dragenter’, ‘dragover’, ‘drop’, ‘dragleave’ and it makes sure to prevent default on each. For dragenter/dragover Red-Border property from styles.CSS is added through the addition of active and the opposite occurs for drop and dragleave 

Once, a Drop is heard we call HandleDrop. Before HandleDrop we  first initialize global variables  filesChecked, followers, and following for later use.  In HandleDrop we make sure to preventDefault browser behaviour and dataTransfer the files into a constant by the name of files in array form. If the files have a length of 0 (no files) the console logs an error. 

Afterwards, the const file holds the first file and if the dropped file doesn't end with “zip” meaning it's not a zip file we also log an error. Then, we log the values into JSZip asynchronously allowing read/write functions on the values. When doing so we call a function on the zip file where we log the zip file on the console to check for issues and we also log the key names from the zip files which displays the files inside of the zip on console

Then, we set a requiredFiles variable which holds values for the files we are looking for in this case, following.json and followers\_1.json and we make a temporary foundFiles variable which holds nothing for now. And then for each of the filenames in zip files (through Object.keys()) we look for the reqFile for each requiredFiles. In case the file paths are different for different users we take a variable to take in the filepath, then change it to a regular file name by the name of normalizedPath just in case. Then using endsWith(‘/{reqFIle}’} or if the filePath itself ends is reqFile we update foundFiles to include the filePath of the reqFile we were looking for

Now for each fileName in requiredFiles, if the fileName is in the foundFiles then we continue on to zip.files and find the foundFile with the filename in the zip file and load it as text using the async function then we call a function on the content. We try to create a constant by the name of JSONObject and set it to the value of JSON.parse(content) then we log the object and the keys in the object for debugging purposes. We create a temporary userNameArr to store usernames if there is a relationships.following present in the jsonObject we log that we found the data and log the data once more for debugging and then if relationships.following is an array, then userNameArr maps relationships.Following and sets all users in relationships.Following as user.String\_list\_data\[0\].value which holds the usernames for people in this sense we load all usernames in to userNameArr, then we push userNameArr into followingArr and log followingArr into console and call check files we then also do this for followers, but the only difference being we don't do relationships.followers we simply do jsonObject as it already has followers. I added a few more logs/errors on the console as there were some prevailing issues when running the code. If the array is not an array for either we logged there is an issue etc. 

If the try part from before we catch the error, and this would reflect an issue parsing the json file. From the previous if where we loaded the content as async(‘text’); we catch error as a function of err where we log there has been an error trying to read the data, if there was an error from before with if fileName is in foundFiles we log the error that fileName is not found. Finally, if there was ever an issue loading the file into JSZip we log error loading the file

We called CheckFiles() in the if block for updating followingArr and followersArr, and filesChecks was incremented as well. checkFiles simply checks if filesChecks has reached the value of 2 meaning both followingArr and followersArr has been populated we can go on to calling processFollowingData();

processFollowingData() uses followersArr and followingArr to process the data to be displayed on the webpage for the user to utilize. 

**Dependencies:**  
	Code: JS, HTML, CSS
